y to find themselves treated as disposable labor abroad.Lan demonstrates how economic disparities, immigration policies, race, ethnicity, and gender intersect in the relationship between the migrant workers and their Taiwanese employers. The employers are eager to flex their recently acquired financial muscle; many are first-generation career women as well as first-generation employers. The domestics are recruited from abroad as contract and "guest" workers; restrictive immigration policies prohibit them from seeking permanent residence or transferring from one employer to another. They care for Taiwanese families' children, often having left their own behind. Throughout Global Cinderellas, Lan pays particular attention to how the women she studied identify themselves in relation to "others"-whether they be of different classes, nationalities, ethnicities, or education levels. In so doing, she offers a framework for thinking about how migrant workers and their employers understand themselves in the midst of dynamic transnational labor flows.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aFilipinosxEmploymentzForeign countries. 0aForeign workers, FilipinozTaiwan. 0aForeign workers, IndonesianzTaiwan. 0aForeign workers, PhilippinezTaiwan. 0aIndonesiansxEmploymentzForeign countries. 0aWomen household employeeszTaiwan. 0aWomen migrant laborzIndonesia. 0aWomen migrant laborzPhilippines. 0aWomenxEmploymentzTaiwan. 0aWomenzTaiwanxEconomic conditions. 0aWomenzTaiwanxSocial conditions. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822387787zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822387787423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers